 @John Galt   I think I can see the root of your question, however it is wrong in principle. The concept of "Ideal temperature" as you put it would be completely arbitrary in the sense that is measured by us (Hence we can come up with any number and say "Eureka, this is it!") To understand the issue we need to shortly see it from a non anthropocentric point of view: What happens is that the planet itself doesn't really care about what temperature there is, the earth in fact will still be happily spinning and evolving long after we have killed ourselves (Either by our wars, climate change or some other natural or non natural factor).
The real question today is: "What is, and how to keep, the ideal BALANCE of climate that will support life as we know it, for the long run" This is not just about temperature, since that is only one factor on this balance. If we manage to answer this big question, we will not 'save the planet' as many people like to state, we will simply save ourselves as humans because this balance will allow us to keep living on earth.
We do not know exactly what this answer is yet, and believe me there's a lot of work running at this very moment trying to catch that perfect balance. However what we DO know for sure is that the way we are going today is drastically affecting this pre-existing natural balance, and that puts our whole civilization at risk, because we are not ready to face the extreme conditions that we are pulling on ourselves as a result. This not only by the emissions, but also by the over exploitation and degradation of the earth systems. Hope this answer helped a bit to raise curiosity about the topic, there's a lot of useful material available on line (Just stay away from any "adjectives" on the title, those are usually silly propaganda from one side or the other)

