 @RedZeshinX  Life as we know it is always ending, that's change.  My issue with climate science, or, more to the point, the politicization of the science, is that the forecasts are attributed with being infallible, irrefutable and precise.  If we were to believe the climatologists' forecasts from the late '60s through early '70s then we'd be in an ice age right about....now.  If there was the political force behind the science then as there is now, and we perceived, anticipated and planned for the worst, then Canada would have moved to Florida.  So far, only our pasty white retirees had that foresight.  The rest of us are still here.  If said retiree thinks their ocean-front property will be their ancestral home they may want to look into Florida's geological history.  Or check their Green Card.  

If temperatures spike as projected in the most dire of models (and remember, they are models, without evidence to support them they remain that, and the climate-gate scandal indicates to me that climatologists are willing to adjust the model to make any input result in the desired output), the feedback loop will make it a short spike because rising sea levels interrupt the gulf stream and enter us into a glacial period.  Steamhouse earth?  Precipitation rains out the carbon and enters the geological carbon cycle.  Vegetation growth increases as part of the biological carbon cycle.  The oceanic carbon cycle factors with both of these with acidification of the water increasing plant growth and shellfish species flourishing.  All of this occurs over deep time.

If I were the hand-wringing type I'd wring my hands over unexpected volcanic activity.  Large, continuous eruptions, or worse yet, super-eruptions, pump the serious green-house gases like SO2 higher into the atmosphere where they have ozone, greenhouse and haze effects resulting in snap climatic cooling.  That's virtually overnight famine territory that you can see occur within a year.  Can't do anything about it though so fuggittaboutit.  I likewise can't change an established climatic feedback loop even if I can change any one input by wearing Birkenstocks and driving a Prius, making Al Gore richer by buying carbon credits or just throwing myself on a funeral pyre and joining the carbon cycle to reduce my emissions over the long term.  It won't matter to future generations because they'll face the same cycle whatever the input levels are.  None of it factors for living life in peace.

