 @urban dweller  The very reasons that made food production so efficient have also made it highly precarious. Most crops are universally one specific strain. Take bananas. They are propagated asexually from offshoots, i.e. cloned. They are genetically identical.  In the 1950s, Panama disease wiped out the dominant variety. A disease resistant strain was developed, after considerable effort. This is what you find in your supermarket today. The same disease has adapted, and is threatening to desiccate this variety.

